The analytical performance of the Nafion-WNCF/BFGCE for Pb2+ detection was investigated in 0.1 M pH 4.5 acetate buffer solution. As displayed in Fig. 5
                        A, Nafion-WNCF/BFGCE showed well-defined stripping peaks of Pb2+ detection. Upon increasing Pb2+ concentrations, the DPASV responses at Nafion-WNCF/BFGCE increased linearly over the concentrations ranging from 0.5 to 100 μg L−1. Meanwhile, there were slight positive shifts in the stripping peak potentials as the concentrations increased. However, the DPASV response of 120 μg L−1 Pb2+ deviated from the linear relationship obtained at a concentration range of 0.5–100 μg L−1 as shown in Fig. 5B. It can be explained that the deposition of Pb2+ on the active sites of WNCF gradually reaches a saturation state at a relatively higher concentration [55]. Additionally, the Nafion-WNCF/BFGCE exhibited a detection limit of 0.2 μg L−1 (S/N = 3), which was below the allowable value of 10 μg L−1 for drinking water proposed by the World Health Organization (WHO) [51]. The analytical performance of Nafion-WNCF/BFGCE for Pb2+ was comparable to those of previously reported bismuth-based electrochemical sensors (Table 1
                        ).
